aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Report for Piper PA-18-150 in Homer, Alaska
The accident occurred in Homer, Alaska.
The accident occurred on September 7, 2012, at 17:00 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Piper PA-18-150.
The defining event was loss of engine power (total).
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was ANC12LA103.
The aircraft registration was N3214D.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were no injuries in the accident.
The private pilot was attempting to land at an off-airport site in a coastal fjord.
During the approach, the private pilot noticed that the propeller didn't seem to be spinning at the correct revolutions per minute.
The private pilot applied carburetor heat.
The private pilot increased the throttle.
The engine did not respond to the private pilot's actions.
The Piper PA-18-150 was unable to reach the intended landing area.
The Piper PA-18-150 impacted the water about 20 yards from shore.
The private pilot attempted to secure the Piper PA-18-150 to the shore.
Tides and water flow swept the Piper PA-18-150 into open water.
The Piper PA-18-150 was later recovered by a fishing vessel.
The engine could not be examined due to the length of time spent in salt water.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident to be the total loss of engine power.
The reason for the total loss of engine power could not be determined because the engine could not be examined.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Homer, Alaska

## Date & Time: 
September 7, 2012, 17:00 Local

## Aircraft:
Piper PA-18-150

## Defining Event:
Loss of engine power (total)

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
ANC12LA103

## Registration:
N3214D

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 None

## Analysis

The private pilot was attempting to land at an off-airport site in a coastal fjord. During the approach, he noticed that the propeller didn't seem to be spinning at the correct rpm. He applied carburetor heat and increased the throttle, but the engine did not respond. The airplane was unable to reach the intended landing area and impacted the water about 20 yards from shore.

The pilot attempted to secure the airplane to the shore, but tides and water flow swept the airplane into open water. The airplane was later recovered by a fishing vessel, but, due to the length of time spent in salt water, the engine was not able to be examined.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:
The total loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because the engine could not be examined because of the extent of time in salt water.

## Findings
Not determined (general) - Unknown/Not determined
